# Outline Format Rules

A.  Purpose
    1.  Defines the layout rules for files in
        `doc/`.
    2.  Each line shows only its local marker;
        uniqueness comes from the marker path.

B.  File type
    1.  Plain text (`.txt`), no Markdown.
    2.  Use quotes only for literal tokens
        (e.g., `@@thought:`).

C.  Style (brevity)
    1.  Keep bullet text concise and brief.
    2.  Prefer short, declarative sentences.

D.  Outline levels and markers
    1.  L1: uppercase (`A.  `).
    2.  L2: numeric; pad 1–9 with `1.  `;
        10+ with `10. `.
    3.  L3: lowercase (`a.  `).
    4.  L4: numeric; pad 1–9 with `1.  `;
        10+ with `10. `.
    5.  Deeper: document before using.

E.  Indentation and alignment
    1.  4 spaces per level.
    2.  Child marker starts under the first
        character of the parent's text (works
        for `9.  ` and `10. ` alike).
    3.  No drift: deeper markers start exactly
        at the parent text-start column (never
        past the wrap column).

F.  Text wrapping (reflow)
    1.  Wrap at ~60 characters.
    2.  Continuation lines start under the first
        character of the bullet text.
    3.  URLs: never break a URL across lines.
        Keep the full URL on one line even if
        it exceeds ~60 chars. Wrap after the
        URL if more text follows.
    4.  Reflow requirement: after any edit,
        reflow the whole file to the ~60 target
        (don't leave early manual wraps).

G.  Spacing
    1.  Blank line between Level 1 sections.

H.  Implied IDs (how uniqueness works)
    1.  Unique ID = marker path
        (example: `C2a.`).

I.  Minimal example (layout)
    1.  Example only (markers shown literally):
        a.  `A.  Title`
        b.  `    1.  Child`
        c.  `        a.  Grandchild`
        d.  `            1.  Great-grandchild`
